================================================================================
KEY FINDINGS SUMMARY
================================================================================

RQ1 – Substitution & GPA:
  - GenAI use displaces traditional study hours (r = -0.157, p < 10^-274)
  - Relationship with GPA is non-linear (inverted-U):
      Low GenAI (<3h):   Post GPA = 3.336
      Mid GenAI (3–12h): Post GPA = 3.366  ← optimal
      High GenAI (>12h): Post GPA = 3.335
  - Traditional hours → Post GPA: r = +0.138 (p < 10^-210)
  - Prior GPA dominates (r = +0.927); direct AI effect is small but real
  - ANOVA across buckets: F = 22.86, p = 1.19e-10

RQ2 – Anxiety & Burnout:
  - Strongest anxiety predictor: Perceived AI Dependency (r = +0.308)
  - GenAI hours also predict anxiety (r = +0.269)
  - COUNTERINTUITIVE: Strict bans increase anxiety and burnout
      Anxiety: 4.89 (ban) vs. 4.12 (permissive) — Δ = +0.77
      High burnout: 29.8% (ban) vs. 23.8% (permissive) — Δ = +6%
  - Kruskal-Wallis: H = 667.7, p = 1.02e-145

RQ3 – Smart Use & Retention:
  - Prompt engineering skill: dominant effect, 11-point gap
      Beginner → 71.1,  Intermediate → 75.8,  Advanced → 82.1
  - Tool diversity: monotonic benefit (r = +0.197)
      1 tool → 72.6,  5 tools → 79.8  (+7.2 pts)
  - ANOVA (Prompt Skill): F = 3012, p ≈ 0
  - Institutional policy: modest secondary effect (~1 pt penalty for bans)
  - HOW you use AI matters far more than WHETHER your institution allows it

POLICY IMPLICATION:
  Replace blanket AI bans with structured, permissive policies.
  Invest in prompt engineering instruction.
  Encourage breadth of AI tool use.
  This simultaneously improves GPA, reduces anxiety/burnout,
  and substantially raises skill retention.
